{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs36 Game instructions\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 When you start the game, click in the game window \u8211- then you'll be able to look around in-game using the mouse. You'll be looking from the point of view of a robot who can dig, shoot lasers, and build stuff. {\b All of the controls are written in-game} \u8211- you can probably learn most of the game by just trying all the controls that are listed, and reading the text that pops up. In fact, why don't you do that right now? You can come back and read the rest of this README if you get stuck.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The main controls are:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Mouse motion: Look around.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab WASD: Move in the four horizontal directions, relative to the way you're looking.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Space: Move upwards.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab (left) mouse button: Do whichever action you have selected.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab ZXCVB: Select different actions (they show descriptions when selected).\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Your robot also levitates a little off the ground, so you can climb up shallow inclines with just the WASD keys.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 You start out looking at a "refinery". Right now, it's a white box, but eventually we will make it look cooler. The resource flow currently goes like this:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 You need metal to build things. You start with some metal, but to get more, you need to refine it. The simplest way to do that is...\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 1.\tx360\tab Be in digging mode. (You start in digging mode, and you can switch back with "z").\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 2.\tx360\tab Point at a nearby rock tile and click it turn turn it to rubble, then click it again to shove it.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 3.\tx360\tab Keep shoving the rock until it gets to the refinery input.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 4.\tx360\tab Repeat until you've gathered enough to make one tile of metal. (The refinery splits rubble into metal and waste rock \u8211- each rubble tile only has a little metal in it. The orangeish waste rock comes out of the refinery opposite the input, and the yellow metal comes out the side. Greener rock has more metal in it.)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 5.\tx360\tab Go near the yellow metal tile and click it to pick it up (note that you can't do this if you're still full of metal \u8211- each tile is 200 cubic meters and you can only carry a total of 421 cubic meters).\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 That's a pretty slow process. There's a lot of ways to do it faster. You can use lasers ("x") to disintegrate more rock at once. You can build more conveyors ("c") to move rubble automatically. You can build other robots ("b") to automatically dig for you. And you can build extra refineries ("v"), although there currently isn't any real advantage to using more than one.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 You can also deconstruct buildings and retreive their metal ("z" mode and click a nearby building), as long as you have enough room to store the extra metal.\par}
